#!/usr/bin/env bash
# Refresh Anthropic's canonical `playground` skill, then open an interactive Claude
# session that reviews every playground skill it can see against the reference and
# proposes fixes/backports - so you can discuss them and apply what you want on the
# spot.
#
# The script does only the mechanical part: refresh the marketplace and snapshot
# the reference. Discovery and judgement are Claude's - it lists its own available
# skills, finds the playground ones, reads each, and reviews it.
set -euo pipefail

marketplace="claude-plugins-official"
ref_src="$HOME/.claude/plugins/marketplaces/$marketplace/plugins/playground/skills/playground"

# Find the repo from this script's own location (~/.bin symlinks to it), so this
# works on any host and even before the skills are activated.
script_dir="$(cd "$(dirname "${BASH_SOURCE[0]}")" && pwd -P)"
repo="$(git -C "$script_dir" rev-parse --show-toplevel)"
snapshot="$repo/tmp/playground-upstream"

echo "==> refreshing $marketplace"
claude plugin marketplace update "$marketplace" || echo "warn: update failed, using the cached copy" >&2

[[ -d "$ref_src" ]] || { echo "reference playground skill not found at $ref_src" >&2; exit 1; }

echo "==> snapshotting the reference skill into ${snapshot#"$repo"/}"
rm -rf "$snapshot"
mkdir -p "$snapshot"
cp -R "$ref_src/." "$snapshot/"

read -r -d '' prompt <<EOF || true
You have a set of available skills (listed in your system context). Some are about
building interactive "playgrounds" (explorers / visual configurators that pair live
controls with a preview and an output). Review each such playground skill against
Anthropic's canonical reference and propose concrete fixes/backports for each.

Reference (the canonical vanilla-HTML playground): ${snapshot#"$repo"/}/SKILL.md and
every file under ${snapshot#"$repo"/}/templates/  - read them first.

Steps:
1. Enumerate every skill available to you whose purpose is building playgrounds.
   Skip the reference itself. If you are unsure a skill qualifies, glob for its
   SKILL.md (search under ~/.claude) and read the description.
2. For each, locate and read its full SKILL.md, and infer which platform it targets.
3. Review it against the reference. Each target is built for a DIFFERENT platform,
   so treat platform adaptations as DELIBERATE, never as gaps - e.g. a different UI
   framework, a live/hot-reloading preview instead of \`open\`, reading state back
   instead of copy-paste, device theming instead of forced dark. Only surface
   SUBSTANCE the reference does better and the target genuinely lacks: playground
   types/templates it doesn't cover, control taxonomies, prompt-output craft,
   pre-populating guidance, or "common mistakes" worth stealing.

Output one section per target skill (labelled by its skill name and SKILL.md path),
each a concise NUMBERED list of suggestions: what to change, why it helps, and where
in that skill it goes. If a target needs nothing, say so plainly.

Then stop and wait - this is a conversation. I'll go through your suggestions and
confirm, deny, or ask about each (I'll refer to them by skill + number). Apply only
the ones I confirm, by editing that skill's SKILL.md in place - for a skill that
lives in this repo, edit the repo source under dotfiles/agents/skills/. Never edit
anything I haven't confirmed, and re-summarize what's left after each round.
EOF

echo "==> opening an interactive review session"
cd "$repo"
exec claude "$prompt" --add-dir "$HOME/.claude"
